Hi!

I recommend to not disable the action in selectionChanged of your IActionDelegate if it is no ISelectionChangedListener (all plugin actions implement ISelectionChangedListener, the shortcut actions do not).

public void selectionChanged(IAction action, ISelection selection);
   if (action instanceof ISelectionChangedListener) { 
      boolean state = ...;
      ...
      action.setEnabled(state);
   }
}

In this case, you need to always check the action state in the run(IAction) method, since run is called whenever pressing the corresponding shortcut, even if the menu item is disabled.

This is not beautiful, but it's a workaround for the issue.

Hi!

> Then, how should the action be disabled when the selection changes ?

Not at all for all actions that are not instance of ISelectionChangedListener.

All actions associated with menu items or toolbar buttons implement ISelectionChangedListener. Actions used for shortcuts are created by Eclipse internally and do currently not implement ISelectionChangedListener. So, a menu item with a shortcut may have more than one action associated, one for the menu item itself and one for the shortcut (the latter is created after the first use of the shortcut). You can enable and disable all actions that are instanceof ISelectionChangedListener, but you must not disable the others.

Here again the example, this time with more comments. I hope this makes it clearer:

public class MyActionDelegate implements IWorkbenchWindowActionDelegate {
 private boolean fState = true;
 ...

 public final void run(IAction action) {
   if (fState) {
      ...  // do something
   }
   else {
      // do nothing; we entered this method although
      // menu item and toolbar button are disabled
   }
 }

 public void selectionChanged(IAction action, ISelection selection);
   fState = ...;   // check if the current selection
                   // enables or disables the action
   if (action instanceof ISelectionChangedListener) { 
      action.setEnabled(fState);  // it's a plugin action associated with
                                  // a menu item or toolbar button, so we
                                  // can disable it
   }
   else {
      // leave action enabled, since it is of a type used Eclipse
      // internally for shortcuts; we must not disable this, otherwise the
      // shortcut will be disabled forever.
   }
 }
}

